The Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) through its Commercial Agricultural Credit Scheme (CACS) has facilitated the disbursement of N622.99 billion for the execution of 600 projects in the agriculture sector. It has also guaranteed another N778.3 million for 5,182 farmers under the Agricultural Credit Guarantee Scheme (ACGS) in the last three months of last year. The N622.99 billion represents the total amount released under the CACS to banks for disbursements since its inception of which N387.27 billion had been repaid as at December 31, 2019. According to data released by the apex bank, Zenith Bank Plc recorded the highest disbursement in terms of amount while First Bank of Nigeria (FBN) Plc had the highest in terms of projects. Zenith Bank disbursed N126.94 billion of the N622.99 billion for 52 projects and recorded the repayment of N83.3 billion of the amount disbursed, while First Bank disbursed N52.99 billion for 104 projects and recovered N44.8 billion. United Bank for Africa (UBA) Plc recorded the second highest disbursement in terms of amount to the tune of N83.53 billion to 52 projects and recorded the repayment of N56.8 billion. Sterling Bank followed with third highest disbursement of N72.43 billion for 43 projects and recorded the repayment of N28.9 billion. Also, total of N778.3 million loans was guaranteed by the CBN for 5,182 farmers under ACGS in the fourth quarter of 2019. This represented a decrease of 35.9 and 8.7 per cent below the levels in the preceding quarter and the corresponding period of 2018, respectively. A sub-sectoral analysis showed that food crops attracted the largest share of 38.5 per cent, with N300 million guaranteed to 1,910 beneficiaries. This was followed by the livestock sub-sector with 20.9 per cent or N162.4 million guaranteed for 607 beneficiaries by the apex bank. In the same vein, mixed crops had N146.6 million or 18.8 per cent in respect of 1,905 beneficiaries while cash crops, fisheries and “others” got N89.4 million, N52.4 million and N27.4 million guaranteed for 469, 158 and 133 beneficiaries, respectively. On state basis, 31 states and the Federal Capital Territory (FCT) benefitted from the scheme in the quarter under review, with highest and lowest sums of N133.4 million accounting for 17.1 per cent, and N2.3 million representing 0.3 per cent guaranteed for Adamawa and Gombe States, respectively.